07897nam a22010215i 9780691188720DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20182019nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911887207 a10.1515/97806911887202doi  a(DE-B1597)502940  a(OCoLC)1053623331  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aQA8.6 7aMAT0390002bisacsh04a51022304aThe Best Writing on Mathematics 2018 /ced. by Mircea Pitici. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Best Writing on Mathematics ;v1100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tMathematics for Human Flourishing -- tHow To Play Mathematics -- tBeauty Is Not All There Is to Aesthetics in Mathematics -- tThe Science of Brute Force -- tComputational Thinking in Science -- tQuantum Questions Inspire New Math -- tTangled Tangles -- tThe Bizarre World of Nontransitive Dice: Games for Two or More Players -- tThe Bingo Paradox -- tThe Sleeping Beauty Controversy -- tWigner's "Unreasonable Effectiveness" in Context -- tLearning and Teaching Interdisciplinary Modeling -- tSix Essential Questions for Problem Solving -- tWhat Does Active Learning Mean for Mathematicians? -- tWritten in Stone: The World's First Trigonometry Revealed in an Ancient Babylonian Tablet -- tQuadrivium: The Structure of Mathematics as Described in Isidore of Seville's Etymologies -- tThe World War II Origins of Mathematics Awareness -- tThe Writing Mathematician -- tContributors -- tNotable Writings -- tAcknowledgments -- tCredits0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe year's finest mathematical writing from around the worldThis annual anthology brings together the year's finest mathematics writing from around the world. Featuring promising new voices alongside some of the foremost names in the field, The Best Writing on Mathematics 2018 makes available to a wide audience many pieces not easily found anywhere else-and you don't need to be a mathematician to enjoy them. These essays delve into the history, philosophy, teaching, and everyday aspects of math, offering surprising insights into its nature, meaning, and practice-and taking readers behind the scenes of today's hottest mathematical debates.James Grime shows how to build subtly mischievous dice for playing slightly unfair games, David Rowe investigates the many different meanings and pedigrees of mathematical models, and Michael Barany traces how our appreciation of the societal importance of mathematics has developed since World War II. In other essays, Francis Su extolls the inherent values of learning, doing, and sharing mathematics, and Margaret Wertheim takes us on a mathematical exploration of the mind and the world-with glimpses at science, philosophy, music, art, and even crocheting. And there's much, much more.In addition to presenting the year's most memorable math writing, this must-have anthology includes an introduction by the editor and a bibliography of other notable pieces on mathematics.This is a must-read for anyone interested in where math has taken us-and where it is headed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMathematics. 7aMATHEMATICS / Essays.2bisacsh1 aArney, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarany, Michael J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenjamin, Arthur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraun, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBremser, Priscilla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemaine, Erik D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.go